Various names used for the same theatre at the University of Washington Digital Collection are: 'Theatre, northeast corner of 3rd Ave. and Madison St., Seattle. Theatre is advertising 'The Taylor Co.' and 'Queen of the Highway'. Known earlier as the Madison St. Theatre, then Cordray's Theatre, it was originally built as a store. title: Native Americans on waterfront in Belltown, ca. 1882
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Waterfronts. 1882-1886. Canoe and Indians. Foot of Vine Street, Cedar Street and Broad Street. A common scene in 1882, '83,'84, '85, '86 at the West end of Vine, Cedar, Broad Streets, Seattle. The canoes were those of Indians on their way from the North to the hop fields of White and Puyallup Valleys. This part of the city front has since been covered by four lines of railroad, wharves, warehouses, shops, streets, etc."

description: Transcribed from photograph: "Churches: Seattle; Architecture. Stewart Street Baptist Church, erected 70-75 years ago ") by a German Methodist Congregation bought by present owners in 1905. Basement put in later and other alterations made in 1925. Photograph taken 1951 but scene shown in photo is same as of this date of this date of August 23, 1952. Adjoining old house in true Victorian style has for sale sign on lawn now. County records do not give either record of erection of Church or old house. Later is private residence and not the parsonage of the church. A large photograph of this scene and other architecture of Seattle in retrospect is now on view at the Henry Art Gallery until Oct. 9th. 76 in all."

title: Potlatch Festival Reception of the Tyee, July 17, 1912
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Golden Potlatch. July 15-20, 1912. Reception of the Tyee. July 17, 1912. E.L. Webster. 2. Joseph Blethen. 3. George Allen. 4. Herbert Schoenfeld. 5. Bert L. Swezea. 6. Tom L. McDonald." From the Potlatch Program printed in the Seattle Times on July 16, 1912: "1:00 pm - Opening spectacle of the Golden Potlatch, 1912. The arrival of the Hyas Golden Potlatch Tyee from the Land of the North. The Hyas Tyee, attended by his tribal chiefs, his Shamans and other dignitaries of this barbaric court, arrives in Elliott Bay on the Goldship Portland. Accompanying him are many "sourdoughs," pioneers of the North, who bring with them the first golden nuggets found in the Great Yukon. They have their "pokes,"their picturesque dog sleds and other equipment of the Northern trails and they come attired in the queer dress of the North, in parks, muk-luka and all the rest. This weird crew will leave the goldship in the stream and make its landing on the waterfront, where the Hyas Tyee and his people will be greeted by the Tilikums of Elttaes who will escort them to the Grandstand on Fourth Avenue between Lenora and Blanchard Streets, where the opening ceremonies will be performed." Location of photograph presumed to be at Grandstand based on newspaper program.

title: Potlatch Festival Reception of the Tyee, July 17, 1912
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Golden Potlatch. July 15-20, 1912. Reception of the Tyee. George Cotterell [i.e. Cotterill] and Hyas Tyee George W. Allen."  From the Potlatch Program printed in the Seattle Times on July 16, 1912: "1:00 pm - Opening spectacle of the Golden Potlatch, 1912. The arrival of the Hyas Golden Potlatch Tyee from the Land of the North. The Hyas Tyee, attended by his tribal chiefs, his Shamans and other dignitaries of this barbaric court, arrives in Elliott Bay on the Goldship Portland. Accompanying him are many "sourdoughs," pioneers of hte North, who bring with them the first golden nuggets found in the Great Yukon. They have their "pokes," their picturesque dog sleds and other equipment of the Northern trails and they come attired in the queer dress of the North, in parks, muk-luka and all the rest. This weird crew will leave the goldship in the stream and make its landing on the waterfront, where the Hyas Tyee and his people will be greeted by the Tilikums of Elttaes who will escort them to the Grandstand on Fourth Avenue between Lenora and Blanchard Streets, where the opening ceremonies will be performed." Location of photograph presumed to be at Grandstand based on newspaper program.

title: Homes on N. 76th St., east of Aurora Ave., 1953
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Houses. Row of builders' houses. North 76th Street, east of Aurora Ave. Built in the 1920's. Looking north. Photo by Werner Lenggenhager, 1953." Home at far right is 1119 N 76th St, Seattle, WA 98103. Note pasted on verso of photograph: "Row of Builders Houses. N 76th Street, just East of Aurora Avenue. South of Street facing north. 1920's. This is a group of similar, substantial, middle-income homes with their neat green lawns, evergreen shrub foundation planting, and varied roofs and porches continuing on down the street exemplified the typical Seattle neighborhood development. The white painted clapboard siding brick fireplaces, unused front yards with service, play yards and garages off the rear alley are particularly representative. The houses were obviously variations of one stock plan, fitting a certain unity to the street. They are good homes with hardwood floors, full basements and hot air heating systems. Many of today's developments still carry on in the spirit of this era, although the value of developing a more complete neighborhood environment with site developments planned for modern living, is having its influence."

title: Madison Park, ca. 1897
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Parks. Madison park. About 1897." Transcribed from back of photograph: "Seattle Wash. 13 July 1963 Give to Miss Eugenia Raymond. Art Department, Seattle Public Library: This is a picture of part of Madison Park about 1897, one morning just before a crew race. Shown is a canoe from Johnson's Canoe Club, Paddled by Martin Martinson (living today in Ballard). The dock is a walk to the boat house, a swing, Johnson's Ice Cream Parlor, and the brick building in the background (the Pioneer Bldg). This was a the extreme south end of Madison Park. Donated by Mrs. Annie Hickey 7728-15 Ave N.E. La 59398 Mrs. Annie Hickey"

title: Rainier Beach branch, Seattle Public Library, ca. 1922
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Public Library. Branches. Rainier Beach branch. 9265? 57th Ave. S." According to the "About This Branch" section of the Rainier Branch website: "Library service in Rainier Beach dates back to 1912, when The Seattle Public Library opened a deposit station at the Montera Pharmacy. The pharmacy was destroyed by fire in November 1917 and the Library lost 453 volumes valued at $428. In 1921 the Library re-established a deposit station at the Rainier Beach Dry Goods store at 9262½ 57th Ave. S., but that closed in 1924." Rainier Beach Dry Goods appears on the left side of the building.

title: View south from 2nd Ave. and Spring St., ca. 1915
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Seattle. Streets. 2nd Ave., c. 1915. Looking south toward L. C. Smith building." Note on back of photograph: "c. 1915 NATIVE SONS AND DAUGHTERS OF SEATTLE Cosmopolitan to a degree, about the only class of citizens limited in numbers are those who have been born in Seattle. This is due to the fact of this city's rapid growth, her population of 330,00 consisting largely of people who have come here from other localities. Perhaps the most picturesque as well as pathetic of all Seattle's types are the real "Native Children," or Siwashes who crouch at the feet of the skyscrapers and offer their quaint Indian baskets, mats, bead work, and other curios to the passing throng of tourists."

title: Crawford and Harrington's wharf, 1882
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Wharves. Crawford and Harrington's wharf. 1882. Copy of original photograph by Werner Lenggenhager." From the Pacific Coast Architecture Database: "Located just to the south of Yesler's Wharf, the Crawford and Harrington Company Wharf was a significant docking spot for cargo ships during the 19th century. The wharf's eastern half would now occupy filled land, crossing Alaskan Way to roughly the foot of the Alaskan Way Viaduct. At the pier's western end was a small shed belonging to the Talbot Coal Yard."

title: Wedgewood homes near 3164 NE 81st St., 1953
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Houses. Wedgewood housing development. East 81st Street west of 35th Ave. N. E. Wood. Developed by Albert Balch. View towards the north. Photo by Werner Lenggenhager, 1953." Transcribed from back of photograph: "WEDGEWOOD SPECULATIVE RESIDENTIAL DEVELOPMENT [i.e. Development] 1953 West of 35th Avenue N. E. at East 81st Street Developer: Albert Balchen [i.e. Balch] In this neighborhood of two hundred homes, the consistently related designs coupled with the preservation of the beautyfull [i.e. beautiful] trees have produced a charming and harmonious development. The modest two and three bed-room homes are variations of the basic plan with a few other designs for special situations. Strange as it seems, few project developers have been willing to save the trees and natural growth abounding in Seattle. Shown is North side of street facing south. Built in the 40's."

title: Main Street School, December 12, 1921
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Seattle Schools. Main Street School. 6th and Main. Built 1873 and called South school; name changed to Main Street school 1889; enlarged 1900; demolished 1921. Frame. Exterior. Front view. Last day of school. Transcribed from back of photograph: “THE LAST DAY OF THE (Main Street) SOUTH SCHOOL was on Dec. 12, 1921, when the classes and their teachers were marched to the newly erected Bailey Gatzert School.  The old Main Street building was later used by the Park Department for a department stable and was finally torn down in recent years.  The foto shows the last classes that entered the building.”

Photo by Asahel Curtis." Transcribed from back of photograph: “Another picture showing the original South School (Main Street) some years after its erection in 1873.  The center building on the trestle is Seattle's first depot, on the Railroad originally constructed to bring coal from Renton and Newcastle.  This is the present site of the “Union Depot” on King street.  The lumber shed of the Retize sawmill shows to the left.  The tracks ran along what is now King street.  The Grant Street bridge later followed this route to the south.”

title: Columbia and Puget Sound Railroad Depot and Machine Shop, ca. 1880
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Seattle Railroad Stations. Columbia and Puget Sound. Railroad depot and machine shop. Built 1876?, demolished by fire June 6, 1889? Photo by Asahel Curtis." Transcribed from back of photograph: “Another picture showing the original South School (Main Street) some years after its erection in 1873.  The center building on the trestle is Seattle's first depot, on the Railroad originally constructed to bring coal from Renton and Newcastle.  This is the present site of the “Union Depot” on King street.  The lumber shed of the Retize sawmill shows to the left.  The tracks ran along what is now King street.  The Grant Street bridge later followed this route to the south.”

title: Classes of South School, opening day, September 2, 1889
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Portraits. Group. Classes of South School, opening day, Sept. 2, 1889. Identified on balcony: Thomas Burke, George Orth, Beckie Schoenfelt, Florence Stowell (Hubbart) teacher, Nellie, Mamie and Don Cowie, Herb Schoenfelt, Blanche Croffut, May Ryther, Alice Carey, Sarah Gottstein, Mamie Chamberlain, Lulu Fuller." Transcribed from back of photograph: “It was a “gala” day - and justified this picture of school, pupils and teachers, as they prepared to enter the new SOUTH SCHOOL for the first classes at the opening of the Fall term on the first Monday of September in 1889.  This and the Central were the city's first brick schools.  On the balcony are Thomas Burke, George Orth, Beckie Schoenfelt, teacher Florence Stowell, Nellie, Mamie and Don Cowie, Herb Schoenfelt, Blanche Croffut, May Ryther, Alice Carey, Sarah Gottstein, Mamie Chamberlain, Lulu Fuller, among others.  This picture through the courtesy of the late Florence Stowell Hubbart.”
intersection: 12th Ave. S. and S. Weller St.

title: King County Courthouse, ca. 1882
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Seattle Buildings. King County Court House. First. 3rd Ave. and Yesler Way . Built 1860; acquired by Seattle 1891. Exterior. Frame. View of front from left side. Ca. 1882. Public school classes were held here from 1864 to 1868." Transcribed from back of photograph: “Public School classes were held in this, originally the “old” County Building, at Third and Jefferson, from 1864-1868, before the community had its first school structure.  Teachers during these years included Dillis B. Ward, Mrs. Wm. Hammond, Mrs. Emma Preston, Mrs. Mary A. Smith, and Miss Carrie Bacon." Building served as the King County Courthouse and then Seattle's first City Hall.  Located on 3rd Ave. between Yesler Way and Jefferson Street.

Transcribed from back of photo: “SOUTH SCHOOL'S “FIRST” BASEBALL TEAM What can be described as the South School's first baseball team was undoubtedly the group photographed above, organized among the students of the school in the spring of 1890. Copy of the photograph was furnished by Floyd Croft, who can be described as the team manager and scorer. With the erection of the Rainier, the T.T. Minor, the Pontius and the Mercer Schools in 1890, interschool competition was inaugurated in 1891.”

title: Potlatch Festival Tyee reception, July 17, 1912
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Golden Potlatch. July 15-20. Reception of the Tyee. View 2." From the Potlatch Program printed in the Seattle Times on July 16, 1912: "1:00 pm - Opening spectacle of the Golden Potlatch, 1912. The arrival of the Hyas Golden Potlatch Tyee from the Land of the North. The Hyas Tyee, attended by his tribal chiefs, his Shamans and other dignitaries of this barbaric court, arrives in Elliott Bay on the Goldship Portland. Accompanying him are many "sourdoughs," pioneers of hte North, who bring with them the first golden nuggets found in the Great Yukon. They have their "pokes," their picturesque dog sleds and other equipment of the Northern trails and they come attired in the queer dress of the North, in parks, muk-luka and all the rest. This weird crew will leave the goldship in the stream and make its landing on the waterfront, where the Hyas Tyee and his people will be greeted by the Tilikums of Elttaes who will escort them to the Grandstand on Fourth Avenue between Lenora and Blanchard Streets, where the opening ceremonies will be performed." Location of photograph presumed to be at Grandstand based on newspaper program.

title: Back of Victorian apartments, ca. 1960
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle; Washington. Houses. Victorian Apt. House on 411-417 9th Ave N. Caption: (See photo of front facade of same Bldg. in your collection.) Backside and yard of Victorian style Apt. house erected in 1890. While front shows a closed facade with its wedding cake decorations, rising sun motives, ever present like a pattern in those early structures, the backside is while plain not without its interesting features. One common outside stairway is used by all and the individual sections now appearing separate units are connected with a little bridge with its flower boxes to add a homey touch while the yard itself is being kept neat and orderly. Werner Lenggenhager."
